    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "nodes": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/fea-predicts-f1717-noncannulated",
      "type": "Claim",
      "name": "FEA accurately predicts ASTM F1717 compression-bending QoIs for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct",
      "description": "The FEA modeling framework, as exercised across the FDA, Ansys, and DePuy Synthes computational environments, accurately predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending loading. This claim is grounded in a comprehensive body of supporting work: mesh convergence studies demonstrating less than 2% change in peak von Mises stress between the medium and fine mesh refinements; material property characterization from tensile coupon testing of Ti-6Al-4V ELI stock; contact mechanics verification against published Hertzian benchmarks; and direct comparison of FEA predictions to N=11 physical test constructs evaluated across two independent laboratories, with all QoI percent differences falling within the pre-established 10% acceptance bound and all E/uval ratios below 1.96. The collective weight of computational verification, material characterization, and multi-laboratory experimental comparison provides strong epistemic support for this claim.",
      "purpose": "Assert the predictive adequacy of the FEA framework for regulatory submission in support of the 510(k) clearance pathway for the non-cannulated pedicle screw design.",
      "scope": "Restricted to static compression-bending under ASTM F1717 protocol; does not extend to fatigue, torsion, or in vivo loading conditions."
    }
  ],
